Reaching on-premises: Site-to-Site V-P-N and Direct Connect.

Two ways bridge AWS to your data centre. A Site-to-Site V-P-N runs an I-P-sec encrypted tunnel over the public internet. It's the fastest to stand up, in minutes with no physical install, and it's encrypted by default, but it's limited in throughput and subject to internet jitter. It has three parts: a Virtual Private Gateway, or V-G-W, on the V-P-C side, or a Transit Gateway V-P-N attachment for the multi-V-P-C case; a Customer Gateway, or C-G-W, representing your on-prem device's public I-P; and the V-P-N Connection that runs the tunnels. Every connection has two tunnels to two AWS-side endpoints, for automatic failover. Routing is either static or dynamic via B-G-P, which is the default for any non-trivial topology and is required for V-P-N CloudHub, the multi-branch pattern.

Direct Connect, or D-X, is a dedicated physical fibre from your facility to an AWS Direct Connect location, bypassing the public internet for consistent bandwidth, predictable latency, and a compliant private path, but it takes weeks to provision. One D-X connection carries Virtual Interfaces, or V-I-Fs: a Private V-I-F for V-P-C resources, a Public V-I-F for AWS public endpoints over the link, and a Transit V-I-F for a Transit Gateway via a D-X Gateway. A Direct Connect Gateway lets one connection reach V-P-Cs in multiple regions.

Production hybrid networks almost always run both: Direct Connect as the primary path, and a V-P-N as the same-day fallback, since D-X takes weeks to provision and the V-P-N bridges the gap.
